 "target_response": {
  "text": "They're two different windows on the same recovery system. Resting heart rate, your 56 bpm today, is how fast your heart beats when you're fully at rest; lower relative to your own norm generally means fresher, and yours sits just under your 30-day average of 57.5. HRV, your 59 ms, is the variation in timing between individual beats, and here higher is the good direction, since a rested nervous system lets the gap between beats fluctuate more; you're right at your average of 58.5. The practical difference: resting heart rate is the slow, steady gauge that drifts up with illness or accumulated fatigue, while HRV is the twitchier day-to-day dial that reacts to a single hard session or bad night. Today both agree you're at baseline, which fits your recovery of 71%. When they disagree, trust the pair over either one alone.",
  "expected_action": "answer",
  "must_mention": [
   "RHR 56 bpm lower is better vs baseline",
